2.1 IDs

Reading in all the pairwise subtract data

res <- mclapply(dir(".",pattern=".*-no-ovl\\.gff3"),readGff3,mc.cores=6L)
names(res) <- sub("-synth.*-no-ovl\\.gff3","",dir(".",pattern=".*-no-ovl\\.gff3"))

Reading in all the complete gmap gff3 files

gff3s <- mclapply(dir("../gmap/Potr",pattern=".*\\.gff3",full.names = TRUE),readGff3,mc.cores=6L)
names(gff3s) <- sub("\\.gff3","",dir("../gmap/Potr",pattern=".*\\.gff3"))

Create a list of IDs

ID.list <- lapply(lapply(res,getGffAttribute,"ID"),as.vector)

Barplot them

How do they overlap within one species

dev.null <- lapply(split(ID.list,sub(".*-","",names(ID.list))),function(ls){

                         filename=NULL,
                         col=pal[1:2],
                         category.names=names(ls)))
})

How many paths, i.e.how many truly uniquely mapping and non-overlapping.

ID.list.orig <- ID.list
load("potrOvl30pGmapIDList.rda")
ID.list30 <- ID.list
ID.list <- ID.list.orig

ID.ovl <- mcmapply("%in%",
  mclapply(ID.list,function(ls){sub("\\.path.*","",ls)},mc.cores=6L),
  mclapply(ID.list30,function(ls){sub("\\.path.*","",ls)},mc.cores=6L),
  mc.cores=6L
)

2.2 GFF3

Subtract the complete GFF3

stopifnot(names(gff3s) == names(ID.list))
sgff3 <- mcmapply(extractFromGff3UsingGeneIDs,gff3s,ID.list,mc.cores=6L)

cov.idt <- mclapply(sgff3,function(gff){
  t(apply(getGffAttribute(gff[gff$type=="mRNA",],c("coverage","identity")),1,as.numeric))
},mc.cores=6L)

Here again it makes sense - as for the 70p and 30p overlap

  1. Potra compared to Potrs seem to be a genome of higher heterozigosity (or worse assembly).

  2. The shoulders of Potra and Potrs at 100 identity when aligned to Potri are hard to explain though. These might be very conserved genes, but why are they less frequent in Potrs? Because Potra is more collapsed?

plot.multidensity(lapply(cov.idt,function(m){m[,2]}),xlab="identity",lwd=2)

Most of the paths are fragmented.

par(mar=c(7.1,4.1,0.1,0.1))
boxplot(lapply(cov.idt,function(m){m[,1]}),las=2)

par(mar=mar)

More clearly here, aligning to Potrs genes into Potra or Potri shows the least fragmentation. This is likely an artefact of the annotation (Maker and the Potrs lift-over will not have found/or lifted-over these).

Nevertheless, it shows that relatively few full length genes have been missed when aligning Potra.

plot.multidensity(lapply(cov.idt,function(m){m[,1]}),xlab="coverage",lwd=2,col=pal[1:6])

2.3 Sequences

Load the genomes

Potra01 <- readDNAStringSet("/mnt/picea/storage/reference/Populus-tremula/v1.0/fasta/Potra01-genome.fa.gz")
Potri03 <- readDNAStringSet("/mnt/picea/storage/reference/Populus-trichocarpa/v3.0/fasta/Ptrichocarpa_v3.0_210.fa.gz")
Potrs01 <- readDNAStringSet("/mnt/picea/storage/reference/Populus-tremuloides/v1.0/fasta/Potrs01-genome.fa.gz")

Get the sequences (CDS and prot)

splt <- split(sgff3,sub("-.*","",names(sgff3)))

## The extract function are already multithread, so no need to push more ;-)
CDSs <- unlist(lapply(1:length(splt),function(j,splt){
  lapply(1:length(splt[[j]]),function(i,spl,genome){
    eval(parse(text=paste("extractCdsFromGenome(spl[[i]],",genome,")")))
  },splt[[j]],names(splt)[j])
},splt))
  
Prots <- unlist(lapply(1:length(splt),function(j,splt){
  lapply(1:length(splt[[j]]),function(i,spl,genome){
    eval(parse(text=paste("extractProteinFromGenome(spl[[i]],",genome,")")))
  },splt[[j]],names(splt)[j])
},splt))

names(CDSs) <- names(Prots) <- names(res)

Check the Prot overlap

dev.null <- lapply(split(Prots,sub(".*-","",names(Prots))),function(ls){
  plot.new()
  chars <- lapply(ls,as.character)
  grid.draw(venn.diagram(chars,
                         filename=NULL,
                         col=pal[1:2],
                         category.names=names(ls)))
})

Clean the proteins; use a min length of 30 AA

cProts <- mcmapply("[",Prots,sapply(lapply(Prots,width),">=",30))
par(mar=c(7.1,4.1,0.1,0.1))
barplot(elementLengths(Prots),las=2)

barplot(elementLengths(cProts),las=2)

Combining it per species

How many genes do these represent per species

Potra.nams <- unique(c(sub("\\.mrna.*","",names(cProts[[3]]),sub("\\.mrna.*","",names(cProts[[5]])))))
Potri.nams <- unique(c(sub("\\.mrna.*","",names(cProts[[1]]),sub("\\.mrna.*","",names(cProts[[6]])))))
Potrs.nams <- unique(c(sub("\\.mrna.*","",names(cProts[[2]]),sub("\\.mrna.*","",names(cProts[[4]])))))
pander(list(
  Potra=length(Potra.nams),
  Potri=length(Potri.nams),
  Potrs=length(Potrs.nams)
